post_cb({"8899814": {"CommentCount": "0", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8899917", "CreationDate": "2012-01-17T18:34:50.753", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-17T18:43:23.487", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "397", "FavoriteCount": "0", "Title": "state of std::vector after std::bad_alloc", "Id": "8899814", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>I'm trying to find a online reference to see the exception safety of several std containers. </p>\n<p>In the case of  <code>std::vector</code>, Does it keep the state previous to the push_back call? I would presume the vector has all its objects still valid (no destructors invoked).  What guarantees offer <code>std::vector</code> after push_back throws a <code>std::bad_alloc</code> exception? </p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><vector><std><exception-safety>", "OwnerUserId": "170521", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8899814_8899917_0": {"section_id": 712, "quality": 0.7058823529411765, "length": 12}, "so_8899814_8899917_2": {"section_id": 712, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n3337": {"so_8899814_8899917_0": {"section_id": 701, "quality": 0.7058823529411765, "length": 12}, "so_8899814_8899917_2": {"section_id": 701, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n4659": {"so_8899814_8899917_0": {"section_id": 741, "quality": 0.7058823529411765, "length": 12}, "so_8899814_8899917_2": {"section_id": 741, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}}, "8899917": {"ParentId": "8899814", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>If it throws, the vector isn't changed. Even not the <code>capacity()</code>.</p>\n<p>According to [container.requirements.general]:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8899814_8899917_0\">Unless otherwise specified (see 23.2.4.1, 23.2.5.1, 23.3.3.4, and 23.3.6.5) all container types defined in this\n  Clause meet the following additional requirements:</p>\n<p id=\"so_8899814_8899917_1\">[...]</p>\n<p id=\"so_8899814_8899917_2\">\u2014 if an exception is thrown by a push_back() or push_front() function, that function has no effects.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "277176", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "8899917", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2012-01-17T18:43:23.487", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-17T18:43:23.487"}});